\crumbs
\h1{The \tt{constant-config} program}

\h2{Interface}
<pre>
  constant-config \it{user} \it{loguser} \it{dir} \it{port} \ti{file}
</pre>
where \ti{user} and \ti{loguser} are system account names,
\ti{dir} is an absolute path name, \ti{port} is a TCP port, and
\ti{file} is a file name.  The port may be specified as a name from
\tt{/etc/services} or a numeric value.

\tt{constant-config} creates the directory \ti{dir} as an
\a{http://cr.yp.to/daemontools/svscan.html}{svscan}-format service
directory, configured to run \tt{constant-httpd} on the TCP port
\ti{port}, running \tt{constant-httpd} as \ti{user} and creating log
files as \ti{loguser}.

\tt{constant-config} creates the directory \tt{\it{dir}/env}
containing files that establish runtime environment variables for
\tt{constant-httpd} via \a{http://cr.yp.to/daemontools/envdir.html}{envdir}.
The variables include \tt{$UID}, \tt{$GID}, \tt{$ROOT}, and
\tt{$REQUESTHOST}.

\tt{constant-config} creates the directory \tt{\it{dir}/root} for
\tt{constant-httpd} to use as its root directory.

\tt{constant-config} creates an empty
\tt{\it{dir}/env/REQUESTHOST}, causing \tt{constant-httpd} to
respect the host named in each request.  To force
\tt{constant-httpd} to use a particular host name, overriding the
host obtained from a request, edit \tt{\it{dir}/env/REQUESTHOST}
after running \tt{constant-config}.
